{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"eac7babb-fac0-4adc-9260-9c3fe6c87fee","content":"\n\nHere's what you need:\n\n### 1. `Directory.Build.props` (at solution root, shared by all 3 projects)\n\n```xml\n<Project>\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n    <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n  <ItemGroup>\n    <PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" />\n  </ItemGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n`EnableMSTestRunner` activates the Microsoft.Testing.Platform runner built into MSTest 3.8.0. `OutputType Exe` is required because each test project becomes a self-contained executable.\n\n### 2. Each `.csproj` — no structural changes needed\n\nThe properties flow in from `Directory.Build.props`. Just make sure a version is resolved for the new package — either:\n\n- **If using Central Package Management** (`Directory.Packages.props`): add the version there:\n  ```xml\n  <PackageVersion Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" Version=\"1.5.0\" />\n  ```\n- **Otherwise**: specify the version directly in `Directory.Build.props`:\n  ```xml\n  <PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" Version=\"1.5.0\" />\n  ```\n\n### 3. CI command change\n\n```diff\n- dotnet test --logger trx\n+ dotnet test -- --report-trx\n```\n\n`--logger trx` is VSTest syntax. With MTP, arguments after `--` are forwarded to the testing platform. `--report-trx` is provided by the `TrxReport` extension you added above. TRX files are written to each project's `TestResults/` folder by default (use `--report-trx-filename <name>` to customize).\n\n### Summary of changes\n\n| What | Change |\n|---|---|\n| `Directory.Build.props` | Add `EnableMSTestRunner`, `OutputType`, and `TrxReport` package |\n| Each `.csproj` | Nothing (properties inherited) |\n| CI command | `--logger trx` → `-- --report-trx` |","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b1df9a5e-69f7-4c21-a197-96a37d5a465b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to migrate 3 MSTest 3.8.0 test projects from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP). They're on .NET 8 SDK and use `dotnet test --logger trx` in CI.\n\nLet me provide a concise, accurate answer based on my knowledge of MSTest 3.8.0 and Microsoft.Testing.Platform.\n\nFor MSTest 3.8.0, the migration to Microsoft.Testing.Platform involves:\n\n1. Setting `<EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>` and `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>` in each test project (or a shared `Directory.Build.props`).\n\n\n2. Adding the `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` NuGet package to enable TRX report generation with MTP.\n3. The `dotnet test` command remains largely the same, though the logger configuration adapts to work with the new platform.\n\nFor MSTest 3.8.0 specifically, I need to enable the built-in Microsoft.Testing.Platform support with `<EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>` and set `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>`. With MTP, the TRX reporting shifts from the traditional `--logger trx` argument to `--report-trx` passed after `--`, so the CI command becomes `dotnet test -- --report-trx`. Rather than configuring this separately for each project, I should consolidate these settings into a shared `Directory.Build.props` file to keep everything consistent. I'm working through the version compatibility for MSTest 3.8.0 and realizing the simplest approach is to just add the TRX report package explicitly to each project rather than relying on profile settings that may have changed between versions. The core setup remains the same: enable the MSTest runner in a shared build props file, then add the TRX extension package where needed. For .NET 8 SDK specifically, `dotnet test` works with MTP-enabled projects through the VSTest bridge that's built in automatically, so `--logger trx` still functions through that layer. If they want the native MTP experience with TRX output, they'd need to use `dotnet run` directly with the appropriate MTP flags instead. The native MTP approach uses `dotnet test -- --report-trx` instead, though the VSTest compatibility layer means `--logger trx` still works—I should just give them the clearest path forward without mixing both paradigms.","outputTokens":2211},"id":"9afd6444-1f5f-42a4-9340-c81c5ceb762f","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:43:13.064Z","parentId":"bc727195-34b0-4fa9-82f9-3d4a9ddbbc0c"}
